TypeScript is a programming language that adds types to JavaScript, making it easier for developers to write code with fewer errors. It's an open-source project developed by Microsoft which extends the capabilities of JavaScript while remaining fully compatible with it.

Duck typing refers to a style of dynamic type checking where the behavior or interface of an object determines its expected usage rather than its declared type. In other words, if you can use something as though it were a duck (e.g., has webbed feet, beak etc.), then treat it like one without worrying about whether it actually IS a bird.

In essence, in TypeScript we define variables using data types such as strings, numbers or booleans; these are used to ensure that only values of specific kinds can be assigned to them. This helps us catch errors early on before they become problematic later down the line when our program executes. On the other hand, duck-typing allows programmers to rely solely upon the methods or properties available within objects instead of their explicit declaration. 

For example, let’s consider this piece of code:

```typescript 
function greet(person: Person) {
    console.log('Hello', person.name);
}

class User{
    name : string;
}
let user = new User();
greet(user); //this will work because even though `user` was not defined as `Person`, but it has all the required property (`name`) so it is treated as `Person`.
```

Here, `greet()` function expects an argument of type `Person`. However, since `User` also possesses the necessary attribute `name`, it satisfies the requirements set forth by `duck-type-checking`; hence the above snippet works fine. But, had we tried passing any value other than `object having "name" property` into the `greet()`, say some random variable, our program would have failed at runtime. So, here comes the benefit of defining Types - Type Safety! We don’t need to worry about what kind of error might occur during run-time execution.


Thus, combining both concepts results in creating robust applications that minimize bugs while being easy-to-use and understand...instructio

