To compare two strings for equality in Java, you can use either the `==` operator or the `equals()` method provided by the String class. The main differences between these methods are as follows:

- Using the `==` operator compares if both variables refer to the same object instance. In other words, this checks whether the string objects being compared point to the exact same memory location. So if you have created two different instances of Strings with the same value then they will return false even though their values are equal. For example: `"Hello".equals("World")` returns False because each is pointing to its own memory address while having different content.

```java
String str1 = "apple";
String str2 = new String("Apple");
if (str1 == str2) {
    System.out.println("Both strings are equal.");
} else {
    System.out.println("Strings are not equal.");
}
```

This output would print'strings are not equal' since the variable names (`str1`, `str2`) reference separate locations in memory containing copies of the original data ("apple", "Apple").

On the contrary, when we use `.equals()` method, It compares the characters within the strings themselves without checking where those character arrays reside in memory. This means that regardless of how many times the string has been instantiated, calling equals on any two equivalent strings always returns true. 

For Example:
``` java 
String str1 = "hello";  
String str2= "world";

if(str1.equals(str2)) //returns false
{
System.out.println("Equal");
}else{
System.out.println("Not Equal");
}

if(str1.equalsIgnoreCase(str2)){//true
	System.out.println("equal ignore case")
	}
```
The above code snippet uses the `equals()` method to check if the contents of the two strings are identical. Since the comparison happens based on the actual character sequence present inside the string itself, it returns True here.

